# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: vitest
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:vitest/api] `test` or `it` defines a set of related expectations.
[src:vitest/api] It receives the test name and a function that holds the expectations to test.
[src:vitest/api] Optionally, you can provide a timeout (in milliseconds) for specifying how long to wait before terminating, or a set of additional options.
[src:vitest/api] The default timeout is 5 seconds, and can be configured globally with `testTimeout`.
[src:vitest/api] If the first argument is a function, its `name` property will be used as the name of the test.
[src:vitest/api] If test body is not provided, the test is marked as `todo`.
[src:vitest/api] When a test function returns a promise, the runner will wait until it is resolved to collect async expectations.
[src:vitest/api] If the promise is rejected, the test will fail.
[src:vitest/api] In Jest, `TestFunction` can also be of type `(done: DoneCallback) => void`.
[src:vitest/api] If this form is used, the test will not be concluded until `done` is called.
[src:vitest/api] You can achieve the same using an `async` function, see the Migration guide Done Callback section.
[src:vitest/api] To use either one is purely a stylistic choice.
[src:vitest/api] If a number, specifies how many times to retry.
[src:vitest/api] If an object, allows fine-grained retry control.
[src:vitest/api] Note that the object configuration is available only since Vitest 4.1.
[src:vitest/api] If set to `0` (the default), the test will run only one time.
[src:vitest/api] This can be useful for debugging flaky tests.
[src:vitest/api] If the tag is not specified in the configuration, the test will fail before it starts, unless `strictTags` is disabled manually.
[src:vitest/api] Attaches custom metadata available in reporters.
[src:vitest/api] Vitest merges top-level properties inherited from suites or tags.
[src:vitest/api] However, it does not perform a deep merge of nested objects.
[src:vitest/api] Prefer using non-nested meta, if possible.
[src:vitest/api] Whether this test run concurrently with other concurrent tests in the suite.
[src:vitest/api] Use `concurrent: false` instead when you need to override inherited or configured concurrency.
[src:vitest/api] When both `concurrent` and `sequential` are specified, `concurrent` takes precedence.
[src:vitest/api] Should this test be the only one running in a suite.
[src:vitest/api] Whether the test should be skipped and marked as a todo.
[src:vitest/api] If it does, the test will pass, otherwise it will fail.
[src:vitest/api] Use `test.extend` to extend the test context with custom fixtures.
[src:vitest/api] This will return a new `test` and it's also extendable, so you can compose more fixtures or override existing ones by extending it as you need.
[src:vitest/api] See Extend Test Context for more information.
[src:vitest/api] Use `test.override` to override fixture values for all tests within the current suite and its nested suites.
[src:vitest/api] This must be called at the top level of a `describe` block.
[src:vitest/api] See Overriding Fixture Values for more information.
[src:vitest/api] `test.scoped` is deprecated in favor of `test.override` and will be removed in a future major version.
[src:vitest/api] If you want to skip running certain tests, but you don't want to delete the code due to any reason, you can use `test.skip` to avoid running them.
[src:vitest/api] In some cases you might run tests multiple times with different environments, and some of the tests might be environment-specific.
[src:vitest/api] Instead of wrapping the test code with `if`, you can use `test.skipIf` to skip the test whenever the condition is truthy.
[src:vitest/api] Use `test.only` to only run certain tests in a given suite.
[src:vitest/api] Sometimes it is very useful to run `only` tests in a certain file, ignoring all other tests from the whole test suite, which pollute the output.
[src:vitest/api] Vitest detects when tests are running in CI and will throw an error if any test has `only` flag.
[src:vitest/api] You can configure this behaviour via `allowOnly` option.
[src:vitest/api] `test.concurrent` marks consecutive tests to be run in parallel.
[src:vitest/api] It receives the test name, an async function with the tests to collect, and an optional timeout (in milliseconds).
[src:vitest/api] `test.skip`, `test.only`, and `test.todo` works with concurrent tests.
[src:vitest/api] When running concurrent tests, Snapshots and Assertions must use `expect` from the local Test Context to ensure the right test is detected.
[src:vitest/api] Note that if tests are synchronous, Vitest will still run them sequentially.
[src:vitest/api] `test.sequential` marks a test as sequential.
[src:vitest/api] This is useful if you want to run tests in sequence within `describe.concurrent` or with the `--sequence.concurrent` command option.
[src:vitest/api] Use `test.todo` to stub tests to be implemented later.
[src:vitest/api] An entry will be shown in the report for the tests so you know how many tests you still need to implement.
[src:vitest/api] Vitest will automatically mark test as `todo` if test has no body.
[src:vitest/api] Use `test.fails` to indicate that an assertion will fail explicitly.
[src:vitest/api] This flag is useful to track difference in behaviour of your library over time.
[src:vitest/api] For example, you can define a failing test without fixing the issue yet due to time constraints.
[src:vitest/api] Tests marked with `fails` are tracked in the test summary since Vitest 4.1.
[src:vitest/api] While `test.each` is provided for Jest compatibility, Vitest also has `test.for` with an additional feature to integrate `TestContext`.
[src:vitest/api] Use `test.each` when you need to run the same test with different variables.
[src:vitest/api] You can inject parameters with printf formatting in the test name in the order of the test function parameters.
[src:vitest/api] Vitest processes `$values` with Chai `format` method.
[src:vitest/api] If the value is too truncated, you can increase chaiConfig.truncateThreshold in your config file.
[src:vitest/api] Alternative to `test.each` to provide `TestContext`.
[src:vitest/api] The difference from `test.each` lies in how arrays are provided in the arguments.
[src:vitest/api] Non-array arguments to `test.for` (including template string usage) work exactly the same as for `test.each`.
[src:vitest/api] Scoped `beforeEach` hook that inherits types from `test.extend`.
[src:vitest/api] Scoped `afterEach` hook that inherits types from `test.extend`.
[src:vitest/api] Scoped `beforeAll` hook that inherits types from `test.extend`.
[src:vitest/api] Scoped `afterAll` hook that inherits types from `test.extend`.
[src:vitest/api] Scoped `aroundEach` hook that inherits types from `test.extend`.
[src:vitest/api] Scoped `aroundAll` hook that inherits types from `test.extend`.
[src:vitest/api] Benchmarking is experimental and does not follow SemVer.
[src:vitest/api] In Vitest terms, benchmark is a function that defines a series of operations.
[src:vitest/api] Vitest runs this function multiple times to display different performance results.
[src:vitest/api] Vitest uses the `tinybench` library under the hood, inheriting all its options that can be used as a third argument.
[src:vitest/api] You can use `bench.skip` syntax to skip running certain benchmarks.
[src:vitest/api] Use `bench.only` to only run certain benchmarks in a given suite.
[src:vitest/api] Use `bench.todo` to stub benchmarks to be implemented later.
[src:vitest/guide-features] This page is a high-level overview of Vitest's capabilities.
[src:vitest/guide-features] If you're new to Vitest, we recommend reading the Learn tutorial first for a hands-on introduction.
[src:vitest/guide-features] Vite's config, transformers, resolvers, and plugins.
[src:vitest/guide-features] Use the same setup from your app to run the tests.
[src:vitest/guide-features] When you modify your source code or the test files, Vitest smartly searches the module graph and only reruns the related tests, just like how HMR works in Vite!
[src:vitest/guide-features] `vitest` starts in `watch mode` **by default in development environment** and `run mode` in CI environment (when `process.env.CI` presents) smartly.
[src:vitest/guide-features] You can use `vitest watch` or `vitest run` to explicitly specify the desired mode.
[src:vitest/guide-features] Start Vitest with the `--standalone` flag to keep it running in the background.
[src:vitest/guide-features] It won't run any tests until they change.
[src:vitest/guide-features] By default Vitest runs test files in multiple processes using `node:child_process`, allowing tests to run simultaneously.
[src:vitest/guide-features] If you want to speed up your test suite even further, consider enabling `--pool=threads` to run tests using `node:worker_threads` (beware that some packages might not work with this setup).
[src:vitest/guide-features] To run tests in a single thread or process, see `fileParallelism`.
[src:vitest/guide-features] Vitest also isolates each file's environment so env mutations in one file don't affect others.
[src:vitest/guide-features] Isolation can be disabled by passing `--no-isolate` to the CLI (trading correctness for run performance).
[src:vitest/guide-features] Vitest provides many ways to narrow down the tests to run in order to speed up testing so you can focus on development.
[src:vitest/guide-features] Use `.concurrent` in consecutive tests to start them in parallel.
[src:vitest/guide-features] If you use `.concurrent` on a suite, every test in it will be started in parallel.
[src:vitest/guide-features] You can also use `.skip`, `.only`, and `.todo` with concurrent suites and tests.
[src:vitest/guide-features] Chai is built-in for assertions with Jest `expect`-compatible APIs.
[src:vitest/guide-features] Notice that if you are using third-party libraries that add matchers, setting `test.globals` to `true` will provide better compatibility.
[src:vitest/guide-features] Vitest provides `jest`-compatible APIs on `vi` object.
[src:vitest/guide-features] Vitest supports both happy-dom or jsdom for mocking DOM and browser APIs.
[src:vitest/guide-features] Vitest supports Native code coverage via `v8` and instrumented code coverage via `istanbul`.
[src:vitest/guide-features] Vitest also provides a way to run tests within your source code along with the implementation, similar to Rust's module tests.
[src:vitest/guide-features] This makes the tests share the same closure as the implementations and able to test against private states without exporting.
[src:vitest/guide-features] Meanwhile, it also brings the feedback loop closer for development.
[src:vitest/guide-features] You can run benchmark tests with `bench` function via Tinybench to compare performance results.
[src:vitest/guide-features] You can write tests to catch type regressions.
[src:vitest/guide-features] Vitest comes with `expect-type` package to provide you with a similar and easy to understand API.
[src:vitest/guide-features] Run tests on different machines using `--shard` and `--reporter=blob` flags.
[src:vitest/guide-features] See `Improving Performance | Sharding` for more information.
[src:vitest/guide-features] Vitest exclusively autoloads environment variables prefixed with `VITE_` from `.env` files to maintain compatibility with frontend-related tests, adhering to Vite's established convention.
[src:vitest/guide-features] By default, Vitest catches and reports all unhandled rejections, uncaught exceptions (in Node.js) and error events (in the browser).
[src:vitest/guide-features] You can disable this behaviour by catching them manually.
[src:vitest/guide-features] Vitest assumes the callback is handled by you and won't report the error.
[src:vitest/guide-features] Alternatively, you can also ignore reported errors with a `dangerouslyIgnoreUnhandledErrors` option.
[src:vitest/guide-features] Vitest will still report them, but they won't affect the test result (exit code won't be changed).
[src:vitest/guide-mocking] Start with the Mock Functions tutorial for a hands-on introduction to `vi.fn`, `vi.spyOn`, and `vi.mock`.
[src:vitest/guide-mocking] When writing tests it's only a matter of time before you need to create a "fake" version of an internal — or external — service.
[src:vitest/guide-mocking] This is commonly referred to as **mocking**.
[src:vitest/guide-mocking] Vitest provides utility functions to help you out through its `vi` helper.
[src:vitest/guide-mocking] You can import it from `vitest` or access it globally if `global` configuration is enabled.
[src:vitest/guide-mocking] Always remember to clear or restore mocks before or after each test run to undo mock state changes between runs!
[src:vitest/guide-mocking] If you are not familiar with `vi.fn`, `vi.mock` or `vi.spyOn` methods, check the API section first.
[src:vitest/guide-mocking] For a simpler and quicker way to get started with mocking, you can check the Cheat Sheet below.
[src:vitest/guide-mocking] Don't forget that a `vi.mock` call is hoisted to top of the file.
[src:vitest/guide-mocking] It will always be executed before all imports.
[src:vitest/guide-mocking] `vi.spyOn` example will not work in the Browser Mode.
[src:vitest/guide-mocking] Don't forget that this only mocks *external* access.
[src:vitest/guide-mocking] In this example, if `original` calls `mocked` internally, it will always call the function defined in the module, not in the mock factory.
[src:vitest/guide-mocking] To mock `Date`'s time, you can use `vi.setSystemTime` helper function.
[src:vitest/guide-mocking] This value will **not** automatically reset between different tests.
[src:vitest/guide-mocking] Beware that using `vi.useFakeTimers` also changes the `Date`'s time.
[src:vitest/guide-mocking] You can set global variable by assigning a value to `globalThis` or using `vi.stubGlobal` helper.
[src:vitest/guide-mocking] When using `vi.stubGlobal`, it will **not** automatically reset between different tests, unless you enable `unstubGlobals` config option or call `vi.unstubAllGlobals`.
[src:vitest/guide-mocking] The environmental variable value will ***not*** automatically reset between different tests.
[src:vitest/guide] Vitest (pronounced as *"veetest"*) is a next generation testing framework powered by Vite.
[src:vitest/guide] You can learn more about the rationale behind the project in the Why Vitest section.
[src:vitest/guide] You can try Vitest online on StackBlitz.
[src:vitest/guide] It runs Vitest directly in the browser, and it is almost identical to the local setup but doesn't require installing anything on your machine.
[src:vitest/guide] It is recommended that you install a copy of `vitest` in your `package.json`, using one of the methods listed above.
[src:vitest/guide] However, if you would prefer to run `vitest` directly, you can use `npx vitest` (the `npx` tool comes with npm and Node.js).
[src:vitest/guide] The `npx` tool will execute the specified command.
[src:vitest/guide] By default, `npx` will first check if the command exists in the local project's binaries.
[src:vitest/guide] If it is not found there, `npx` will look in the system's `$PATH` and execute it if found.
[src:vitest/guide] If the command is not found in either location, `npx` will install it in a temporary location prior to execution.
[src:vitest/guide] As an example, we will write a simple test that verifies the output of a function that adds two numbers.
[src:vitest/guide] By default, tests must contain `.test.` or `.spec.` in their file name.
[src:vitest/guide] If you are using Bun as your package manager, make sure to use `bun run test` command instead of `bun test`, otherwise Bun will run its own test runner.
[src:vitest/guide] Continue to Writing Tests to learn about organizing tests, reading test output, and the core testing patterns you'll use every day.
[src:vitest/guide] To run tests once without watching for file changes, use `vitest run`.
[src:vitest/guide] You can also pass additional flags like `--reporter` or `--coverage`.
[src:vitest/guide] For a full list of CLI options, run `npx vitest --help` or see the CLI guide.
[src:vitest/guide] Vitest reads your `vite.config.*` by default, so your existing Vite plugins and configuration work out-of-the-box.
[src:vitest/guide] You can also create a dedicated `vitest.config.*` for test-specific settings.
[src:vitest/guide] We also provided an official extension for Visual Studio Code to enhance your testing experience with Vitest.
[src:vitest/guide] If you have questions or need help, reach out to the community at Discord and GitHub Discussions.
[src:vitest/javascript] Web browsers have a dedicated JavaScript engine that executes the client code.
[src:vitest/javascript] These engines are also utilized in some servers and a variety of apps.
[src:vitest/javascript] The most popular runtime system for non-browser usage is Node.js.
[src:vitest/javascript] JavaScript is a high-level, often just-in-time–compiled language that conforms to the ECMAScript standard.
[src:vitest/javascript] It has dynamic typing, prototype-based object-orientation, and first-class functions.
[src:vitest/javascript] It is multi-paradigm, supporting event-driven, functional, and imperative programming styles.
[src:vitest/javascript] It has application programming interfaces (APIs) for working with text, dates, regular expressions, standard data structures, and the Document Object Model (DOM).
[src:vitest/javascript] The ECMAScript standard does not include any input/output (I/O), such as networking, storage, or graphics facilities.
[src:vitest/javascript] In practice, the web browser or other runtime system provides JavaScript APIs for I/O.
[src:vitest/javascript] Although Java and JavaScript are similar in name and syntax, the two languages are distinct and differ greatly in design.
[src:vitest/javascript] The first popular web browser with a graphical user interface, Mosaic, was released in 1993.
[src:vitest/javascript] The lead developers of Mosaic then founded the Netscape corporation, which released a more polished browser, Netscape Navigator, in 1994.
[src:vitest/javascript] During these formative years of the Web, web pages could only be static, lacking the capability for dynamic behavior after the page was loaded in the browser.
[src:vitest/javascript] There was a desire in the flourishing web development scene to remove this limitation, so in 1995, Netscape decided to add a programming language to Navigator.
[src:vitest/javascript] They pursued two routes to achieve this: collaborating with Sun Microsystems to embed the Java language, while also hiring Brendan Eich to embed the Scheme language.
[src:vitest/javascript] The goal was a "language for the masses", "to help nonprogrammers create dynamic, interactive Web sites".
[src:vitest/javascript] Netscape management soon decided that the best option was for Eich to devise a new language, with syntax similar to Java and less like Scheme or other extant scripting languages.
[src:vitest/javascript] Although the new language and its interpreter implementation were called LiveScript when first shipped as part of a Navigator beta in September 1995, the name was changed to JavaScript for the official release in December.
[src:vitest/javascript] The choice of the *JavaScript* name has caused confusion, implying that it is directly related to Java.
[src:vitest/javascript] At the time, the dot-com boom had begun and Java was a popular new language, so Eich considered the JavaScript name a marketing ploy by Netscape.
[src:vitest/javascript] Microsoft debuted Internet Explorer in 1995, leading to a browser war with Netscape.
[src:vitest/javascript] On the JavaScript front, Microsoft created its own interpreter called JScript.
[src:vitest/javascript] Microsoft first released JScript in 1996, alongside initial support for CSS and extensions to HTML.
[src:vitest/javascript] Each of these implementations was noticeably different from their counterparts in Netscape Navigator.
[src:vitest/javascript] These differences made it difficult for developers to make their websites work well in both browsers, leading to widespread use of "best viewed in Netscape" and "best viewed in Internet Explorer" logos for several years.
[src:vitest/javascript] In November 1996, Netscape submitted JavaScript to Ecma International, as the starting point for a standard specification that all browser vendors could conform to.
[src:vitest/javascript] This led to the official release of the first ECMAScript language specification in June 1997.
[src:vitest/javascript] The standards process continued for a few years, with the release of ECMAScript 2 in June 1998 and ECMAScript 3 in December 1999.
[src:vitest/javascript] However, the effort to fully standardize the language was undermined by Microsoft gaining an increasingly dominant position in the browser market.
[src:vitest/javascript] By the early 2000s, Internet Explorer's market share reached 95%.
[src:vitest/javascript] This meant that JScript became the de facto standard for client-side scripting on the Web.
[src:vitest/javascript] Microsoft initially participated in the standards process and implemented some proposals in its JScript language, but eventually it stopped collaborating on ECMA work.
[src:vitest/javascript] During the period of Internet Explorer dominance in the early 2000s, client-side scripting was stagnant.
[src:vitest/javascript] This started to change in 2004, when the successor of Netscape, Mozilla, released the Firefox browser.
[src:vitest/javascript] Firefox was well received by many, taking significant market share from Internet Explorer.
[src:vitest/javascript] In 2005, Mozilla joined ECMA International, and work started on the ECMAScript for XML (E4X) standard.
[src:vitest/javascript] This led to Mozilla working jointly with Macromedia (later acquired by Adobe Systems), who were implementing E4X in their ActionScript 3 language, which was based on an ECMAScript 4 draft.
[src:vitest/javascript] The goal became standardizing ActionScript 3 as the new ECMAScript 4.
[src:vitest/javascript] To this end, Adobe Systems released the Tamarin implementation as an open source project.
[src:vitest/javascript] However, Tamarin and ActionScript 3 were too different from established client-side scripting, and without cooperation from Microsoft, ECMAScript 4 never reached fruition.
[src:vitest/javascript] Meanwhile, very important developments were occurring in open-source communities not affiliated with ECMA work.
[src:vitest/javascript] In 2005, Jesse James Garrett released a white paper in which he coined the term Ajax and described a set of technologies, of which JavaScript was the backbone, to create web applications where data can be loaded in the background, avoiding the need for full page reloads.
[src:vitest/javascript] This sparked a renaissance period of JavaScript, spearheaded by open-source libraries and the communities that formed around them.
[src:vitest/javascript] Many new libraries were created, including jQuery, Prototype, Dojo Toolkit, and MooTools.
[src:vitest/javascript] Google debuted its Chrome browser in 2008, with the V8 JavaScript engine that was faster than its competition.
[src:vitest/javascript] The key innovation was just-in-time compilation (JIT), so other browser vendors needed to overhaul their engines for JIT.
[src:vitest/javascript] In July 2008, these disparate parties came together for a conference in Oslo.
[src:vitest/javascript] This led to the eventual agreement in early 2009 to combine all relevant work and drive the language forward.
[src:vitest/javascript] The result was the ECMAScript 5 standard, released in December 2009.
[src:vitest/javascript] Ambitious work on the language continued for several years, culminating in an extensive collection of additions and refinements being formalized with the publication of ECMAScript 6 in 2015.
[src:vitest/javascript] The creation of Node.js in 2009 by Ryan Dahl sparked a significant increase in the usage of JavaScript outside of web browsers.
[src:vitest/javascript] Node combines the V8 engine, an event loop, and I/O APIs, thereby providing a stand-alone JavaScript runtime system.
[src:vitest/javascript] As of 2018, Node had been used by millions of developers, and npm had the most modules of any package manager in the world.
[src:vitest/javascript] The ECMAScript draft specification is currently maintained openly on GitHub, and editions are produced via regular annual snapshots.
[src:vitest/javascript] Potential revisions to the language are vetted through a comprehensive proposal process.
[src:vitest/javascript] Now, instead of edition numbers, developers check the status of upcoming features individually.
[src:vitest/javascript] The current JavaScript ecosystem has many libraries and frameworks, established programming practices, and substantial usage of JavaScript outside of web browsers.
[src:vitest/javascript] Plus, with the rise of single-page applications and other JavaScript-heavy websites, several transpilers have been created to aid the development process.
[src:vitest/javascript] As of 2025, the overwhelming majority of websites (98.9%) use JavaScript for client side webpage behavior.
[src:vitest/javascript] "JavaScript" is a trademark of Oracle Corporation in the United States.
[src:vitest/javascript] The trademark was originally issued to Sun Microsystems on 6 May 1997, and was transferred to Oracle when they acquired Sun in 2009.
[src:vitest/javascript] A letter was circulated in September 2024, spearheaded by Ryan Dahl, calling on Oracle to free the JavaScript trademark.
[src:vitest/javascript] Brendan Eich, the original creator of JavaScript, was among the over 14,000 signatories who supported the initiative.
[src:vitest/javascript] JavaScript is the dominant client-side scripting language of the Web, with 99% of all websites using it for this purpose.
[src:vitest/javascript] Scripts are embedded in or included from HTML documents and interact with the DOM.
[src:vitest/javascript] All major web browsers have a built-in JavaScript engine that executes the code on the user's device.
[src:vitest/javascript] Over 80% of websites use a third-party JavaScript library or web framework as part of their client-side scripting.
[src:vitest/javascript] Other notable ones include Angular, Bootstrap, Lodash, Modernizr, React, Underscore, and Vue.
[src:vitest/javascript] Multiple options can be used in conjunction, such as jQuery and Bootstrap.
[src:vitest/javascript] However, the term "Vanilla JS" was coined for websites not using any libraries or frameworks at all, instead relying entirely on standard JavaScript functionality.
[src:vitest/javascript] The use of JavaScript has expanded beyond its web browser roots.
[src:vitest/javascript] JavaScript engines are now embedded in a variety of other software systems, both for server-side website deployments and non-browser applications.
[src:vitest/javascript] Initial attempts at promoting server-side JavaScript usage were Netscape Enterprise Server and Microsoft's Internet Information Services, but they were small niches.
[src:vitest/javascript] Server-side usage eventually started to grow in the late 2000s, with the creation of Node.js and other approaches.
[src:vitest/javascript] Electron, Cordova, React Native, and other application frameworks have been used to create many applications with behavior implemented in JavaScript.
[src:vitest/javascript] Other non-browser applications include Adobe Acrobat support for scripting PDF documents and GNOME Shell extensions written in JavaScript.
[src:vitest/javascript] Oracle used to provide Nashorn, a JavaScript interpreter, as part of their Java Development Kit (JDK) API library along with **jjs** a command line interpreter as of JDK version 8.
[src:vitest/javascript] As a replacement Oracle offered GraalJS which can also be used with the OpenJDK which allows one to create and reference Java objects in JavaScript code and add runtime scripting in JavaScript to applications written in Java.
[src:vitest/javascript] JavaScript has been used in some embedded systems, usually by leveraging Node.js.
[src:vitest/javascript] The first JavaScript engines were interpreters of the source code, but modern engines use just-in-time compilation to improve performance.
[src:vitest/javascript] JavaScript engines are typically developed by web browser vendors, and every major browser includes one.
[src:vitest/javascript] In a browser, the JavaScript engine runs in concert with the rendering engine via the Document Object Model and Web IDL bindings.
[src:vitest/javascript] However, the use of JavaScript engines is not limited to browsers; For example, the V8 engine is a core component of the Node.js runtime system.
[src:vitest/javascript] They are also called ECMAScript engines, after the official name of the specification.
[src:vitest/javascript] With the advent of WebAssembly, some engines can also execute this code in the same sandbox as regular JavaScript code.
[src:vitest/javascript] A JavaScript engine must be embedded within a runtime system (such as a web browser or a standalone system) to enable scripts to interact with the broader environment.
[src:vitest/javascript] The runtime system includes the necessary APIs for input/output operations, such as networking, storage, and graphics, and provides the ability to import scripts.
[src:vitest/javascript] JavaScript is a single-threaded language.
[src:vitest/javascript] The runtime processes messages from a queue one at a time, and it calls a function associated with each new message, creating a call stack frame with the function's arguments and local variables.
[src:vitest/javascript] The call stack shrinks and grows based on the function's needs.
[src:vitest/javascript] When the call stack is empty upon function completion, JavaScript proceeds to the next message in the queue.
[src:vitest/javascript] This is called the event loop, described as "run to completion" because each message is fully processed before the next message is considered.
[src:vitest/javascript] However, the language's concurrency model describes the event loop as non-blocking: program I/O is performed using events and callback functions.
[src:vitest/javascript] This means, for example, that JavaScript can process a mouse click while waiting for a database query to return information.
[src:vitest/javascript] The notable standalone runtimes are Node.js, Deno, and Bun.
[src:vitest/javascript] The following features are common to all conforming ECMAScript implementations unless explicitly specified otherwise.
[src:vitest/javascript] The number of cited reserved words including keywords is 50–60 and varies depending on the implementation.
[src:vitest/javascript] JavaScript supports much of the structured programming syntax from C (e.g., `if` statements, `while` loops, `switch` statements, `do while` loops, etc.).
[src:vitest/javascript] One partial exception is scoping: originally JavaScript only had function scoping with `var`; block scoping was added in ECMAScript 2015 with the keywords `let` and `const`.
[src:vitest/javascript] Like C, JavaScript makes a distinction between expressions and statements.
[src:vitest/javascript] One syntactic difference from C is automatic semicolon insertion, which allow semicolons (which terminate statements) to be omitted.
[src:vitest/javascript] JavaScript is weakly typed, which means certain types are implicitly cast depending on the operation used.
[src:vitest/javascript] Values are cast to numbers by casting to strings and then casting the strings to numbers.
[src:vitest/javascript] These processes can be modified by defining `toString` and `valueOf` functions on the prototype for string and number casting respectively.
[src:vitest/javascript] JavaScript has received criticism for the way it implements these conversions as the complexity of the rules can be mistaken for inconsistency.
[src:vitest/javascript] For example, when adding a number to a string, the number will be cast to a string before performing concatenation, but when subtracting a number from a string, the string is cast to a number before performing subtraction.
[src:vitest/javascript] Often also mentioned is `{} + []` resulting in `0` (number).
[src:vitest/javascript] This is misleading: the `{}` is interpreted as an empty code block instead of an empty object, and the empty array is cast to a number by the remaining unary `+` operator.
[src:vitest/javascript] If the expression is wrapped in parentheses - `({} + [])` – the curly brackets are interpreted as an empty object and the result of the expression is `"[object Object]"` as expected.
[src:vitest/javascript] JavaScript is dynamically typed like most other scripting languages.
[src:vitest/javascript] A type is associated with a value rather than an expression.
[src:vitest/javascript] For example, a variable initially bound to a number may be reassigned to a string.
[src:vitest/javascript] JavaScript supports various ways to test the type of objects, including duck typing.
[src:vitest/javascript] JavaScript includes an `eval` function that can execute statements provided as strings at run-time.
[src:vitest/javascript] In JavaScript, an object is an associative array, augmented with a prototype (see below); each key provides the name for an object property, and there are two syntactical ways to specify such a name: dot notation (`obj.x = 10`) and bracket notation (`obj["x"] = 10`).
[src:vitest/javascript] A property may be added, rebound, or deleted at run-time.
[src:vitest/javascript] Most properties of an object (and any property that belongs to an object's prototype inheritance chain) can be enumerated using a `for...in` loop.
[src:vitest/javascript] JavaScript uses prototypes where many other object-oriented languages use classes for inheritance, but it's still possible to simulate most class-based features with the prototype system.
[src:vitest/javascript] Additionally, ECMAScript version 6 (released June 2015) introduced the keywords **class**, **extends** and **super**, which serve as syntactic sugar to abstract the underlying prototypal inheritance system with a more conventional interface.
[src:vitest/javascript] Constructors are declared by specifying a method named **constructor**, and all classes are automatically subclasses of the base class Object, similarly to Java.
[src:vitest/javascript] Though the underlying object mechanism is still based on prototypes, the newer syntax is similar to other object oriented languages.
[src:vitest/javascript] Private variables are declared by prefixing the field name with a number sign (#), and polymorphism is not directly supported, although it can be emulated by manually calling different functions depending on the number and type of arguments provided.
[src:vitest/javascript] Functions double as object constructors, along with their typical role.
[src:vitest/javascript] Prefixing a function call with *new* will create an instance of a prototype, inheriting properties and methods from the constructor (including properties from the `Object` prototype).
[src:vitest/javascript] ECMAScript 5 offers the `Object.create` method, allowing explicit creation of an instance without automatically inheriting from the `Object` prototype (older environments can assign the prototype to `null`).
[src:vitest/javascript] The constructor's `prototype` property determines the object used for the new object's internal prototype.
[src:vitest/javascript] New methods can be added by modifying the prototype of the function used as a constructor.
[src:vitest/javascript] JavaScript's built-in classes, such as `Array` and `Object`, also have prototypes that can be modified.
[src:vitest/javascript] However, it's generally considered bad practice to modify built-in objects, because third-party code may use or inherit methods and properties from these objects, and may not expect the prototype to be modified.
[src:vitest/javascript] Unlike in many object-oriented languages, in JavaScript there is no distinction between a function definition and a method definition.
[src:vitest/javascript] Rather, the distinction occurs during function calling.
[src:vitest/javascript] When a function is called as a method of an object, the function's local *this* keyword is bound to that object for that invocation.
[src:vitest/javascript] JavaScript functions are first-class; a function is considered to be an object.
[src:vitest/javascript] As such, a function may have properties and methods, such as `.call()` and `.bind()`.
[src:vitest/javascript] A *nested* function is a function defined within another function.
[src:vitest/javascript] It is created each time the outer function is invoked.
[src:vitest/javascript] In addition, each nested function forms a lexical closure: the lexical scope of the outer function (including any constant, local variable, or argument value) becomes part of the internal state of each inner function object, even after execution of the outer function concludes.
[src:vitest/javascript] JavaScript also supports anonymous functions.
[src:vitest/javascript] JavaScript supports implicit and explicit delegation.
[src:vitest/javascript] JavaScript natively supports various function-based implementations of Role patterns like Traits and Mixins.
[src:vitest/javascript] Such a function defines additional behavior by at least one method bound to the `this` keyword within its `function` body.
[src:vitest/javascript] A Role then has to be delegated explicitly via `call` or `apply` to objects that need to feature additional behavior that is not shared via the prototype chain.
[src:vitest/javascript] Whereas explicit function-based delegation does cover composition in JavaScript, implicit delegation already happens every time the prototype chain is walked in order to, e.g., find a method that might be related to but is not directly owned by an object.
[src:vitest/javascript] Once the method is found it gets called within this object's context.
[src:vitest/javascript] Thus inheritance in JavaScript is covered by a delegation automatism that is bound to the prototype property of constructor functions.
[src:vitest/javascript] An indefinite number of parameters can be passed to a function.
[src:vitest/javascript] The function can access them through formal parameters and also through the local `arguments` object.
[src:vitest/javascript] Variadic functions can also be created by using the `bind` method.
[src:vitest/javascript] Like in many scripting languages, arrays and objects (associative arrays in other languages) can each be created with a succinct shortcut syntax.
[src:vitest/javascript] In fact, these literals form the basis of the JSON data format.
[src:vitest/javascript] JavaScript supports regular expressions for text searches and manipulation.
[src:vitest/javascript] A built-in Promise object provides functionality for handling promises and associating handlers with an asynchronous action's eventual result.
[src:vitest/javascript] JavaScript supplies combinator methods, which allow developers to combine multiple JavaScript promises and do operations based on different scenarios.
[src:vitest/javascript] The methods introduced are: Promise.race, Promise.all, Promise.allSettled and Promise.any.
[src:vitest/javascript] Async/await allows an asynchronous, non-blocking function to be structured in a way similar to an ordinary synchronous function.
[src:vitest/javascript] Asynchronous, non-blocking code can be written, with minimal overhead, structured similarly to traditional synchronous, blocking code.
[src:vitest/javascript] Variables in JavaScript can be defined using either the `var`, `let` or `const` keywords.
[src:vitest/javascript] Variables defined without keywords will be defined at the global scope.
[src:vitest/javascript] Arrow functions were first introduced in 6th Edition – ECMAScript 2015.
[src:vitest/javascript] They shorten the syntax for writing functions in JavaScript.
[src:vitest/javascript] Arrow functions are anonymous, so a variable is needed to refer to them in order to invoke them after their creation, unless surrounded by parenthesis and executed immediately.
