[src:vitest/javascript] Note the comments in the examples above, all of which were preceded with two forward slashes.
[src:vitest/javascript] More examples can be found at the Wikibooks page on JavaScript syntax examples.
[src:vitest/javascript] JavaScript and the DOM provide the potential for malicious authors to deliver scripts to run on a client computer via the Web.
[src:vitest/javascript] Browser authors minimize this risk using two restrictions.
[src:vitest/javascript] First, scripts run in a sandbox in which they can only perform Web-related actions, not general-purpose programming tasks like creating files.
[src:vitest/javascript] Second, scripts are constrained by the same-origin policy: scripts from one website do not have access to information such as usernames, passwords, or cookies sent to another site.
[src:vitest/javascript] Most JavaScript-related security bugs are breaches of either the same origin policy or the sandbox.
[src:vitest/javascript] There are subsets of general JavaScript—ADsafe, Secure ECMAScript (SES)—that provide greater levels of security, especially on code created by third parties (such as advertisements).
[src:vitest/javascript] Closure Toolkit is another project for safe embedding and isolation of third-party JavaScript and HTML.
[src:vitest/javascript] Content Security Policy is the main intended method of ensuring that only trusted code is executed on a Web page.
[src:vitest/javascript] A common JavaScript-related security problem is cross-site scripting (XSS), a violation of the same-origin policy.
[src:vitest/javascript] XSS vulnerabilities occur when an attacker can cause a target Website, such as an online banking website, to include a malicious script in the webpage presented to a victim.
[src:vitest/javascript] The script in this example can then access the banking application with the privileges of the victim, potentially disclosing secret information or transferring money without the victim's authorization.
[src:vitest/javascript] One important solution to XSS vulnerabilities is HTML sanitization.
[src:vitest/javascript] Some browsers include partial protection against *reflected* XSS attacks, in which the attacker provides a URL including malicious script.
[src:vitest/javascript] However, even users of those browsers are vulnerable to other XSS attacks, such as those where the malicious code is stored in a database.
[src:vitest/javascript] Only correct design of Web applications on the server-side can fully prevent XSS.
[src:vitest/javascript] XSS vulnerabilities can also occur because of implementation mistakes by browser authors.
[src:vitest/javascript] Another cross-site vulnerability is cross-site request forgery (CSRF).
[src:vitest/javascript] In CSRF, code on an attacker's site tricks the victim's browser into taking actions the user did not intend at a target site (like transferring money at a bank).
[src:vitest/javascript] When target sites rely solely on cookies for request authentication, requests originating from code on the attacker's site can carry the same valid login credentials of the initiating user.
[src:vitest/javascript] In general, the solution to CSRF is to require an authentication value in a hidden form field, and not only in the cookies, to authenticate any request that might have lasting effects.
[src:vitest/javascript] Checking the HTTP Referrer header can also help.
[src:vitest/javascript] "JavaScript hijacking" is a type of CSRF attack in which a `<script>` tag on an attacker's site exploits a page on the victim's site that returns private information such as JSON or JavaScript.
[src:vitest/javascript] Developers of client-server applications must recognize that untrusted clients may be under the control of attackers.
[src:vitest/javascript] The author of an application should not assume that their JavaScript code will run as intended (or at all) because any secret embedded in the code could be extracted by a determined adversary.
[src:vitest/javascript] Package management systems such as npm and Bower are popular with JavaScript developers.
[src:vitest/javascript] Such systems allow a developer to easily manage their program's dependencies upon other developers' program libraries.
[src:vitest/javascript] Developers trust that the maintainers of the libraries will keep them secure and up to date, but that is not always the case.
[src:vitest/javascript] A vulnerability has emerged because of this blind trust.
[src:vitest/javascript] Relied-upon libraries can have new releases that cause bugs or vulnerabilities to appear in all programs that rely upon the libraries.
[src:vitest/javascript] Inversely, a library can go unpatched with known vulnerabilities out in the wild.
[src:vitest/javascript] In a study done looking over a sample of 133,000 websites, researchers found 37% of the websites included a library with at least one known vulnerability.
[src:vitest/javascript] This occurred in March 2016 when Azer Koçulu removed his repository from npm.
[src:vitest/javascript] This caused tens of thousands of programs and websites depending upon his libraries to break.
[src:vitest/javascript] JavaScript provides an interface to a wide range of browser capabilities, some of which may have flaws such as buffer overflows.
[src:vitest/javascript] These flaws can allow attackers to write scripts that would run any code they wish on the user's system.
[src:vitest/javascript] This code is not by any means limited to another JavaScript application.
[src:vitest/javascript] For example, a buffer overrun exploit can allow an attacker to gain access to the operating system's API with superuser privileges.
[src:vitest/javascript] These flaws have affected major browsers including Firefox, Internet Explorer, and Safari.
[src:vitest/javascript] Plugins, such as video players, Adobe Flash, and the wide range of ActiveX controls enabled by default in Microsoft Internet Explorer, may also have flaws exploitable via JavaScript (such flaws have been exploited in the past).
[src:vitest/javascript] In Windows Vista, Microsoft has attempted to contain the risks of bugs such as buffer overflows by running the Internet Explorer process with limited privileges.
[src:vitest/javascript] Google Chrome similarly confines its page renderers to their own "sandbox".
[src:vitest/javascript] Web browsers are capable of running JavaScript outside the sandbox, with the privileges necessary to, for example, create or delete files.
[src:vitest/javascript] Such privileges are not intended to be granted to code from the Web.
[src:vitest/javascript] Incorrectly granting privileges to JavaScript from the Web has played a role in vulnerabilities in both Internet Explorer and Firefox.
[src:vitest/javascript] In Windows XP Service Pack 2, Microsoft demoted JScript's privileges in Internet Explorer.
[src:vitest/javascript] Microsoft Windows allows JavaScript source files on a computer's hard drive to be launched as general-purpose, non-sandboxed programs (see: Windows Script Host).
[src:vitest/javascript] This makes JavaScript (like VBScript) a theoretically viable vector for a Trojan horse, although JavaScript Trojan horses are uncommon in practice.
[src:vitest/javascript] In 2015, a JavaScript-based proof-of-concept implementation of a rowhammer attack was described in a paper by security researchers.
[src:vitest/javascript] In 2017, a JavaScript-based attack via browser was demonstrated that could bypass ASLR.
[src:vitest/javascript] In 2018, the paper that announced the Spectre attacks against Speculative Execution in Intel and other processors included a JavaScript implementation.
[src:vitest/javascript] Important tools have evolved with the language.
[src:vitest/javascript] A common misconception is that JavaScript is directly related to Java.
[src:vitest/javascript] Both indeed have a C-like syntax (the C language being their most immediate common ancestor language).
[src:vitest/javascript] They are also typically sandboxed, and JavaScript was designed with Java's syntax and standard library in mind.
[src:vitest/javascript] In particular, all Java keywords were reserved in original JavaScript, JavaScript's standard library follows Java's naming conventions, and JavaScript's `Math` and `Date` objects are based on classes from Java 1.0.
[src:vitest/javascript] Both languages first appeared in 1995, but Java was developed by James Gosling of Sun Microsystems and JavaScript by Brendan Eich of Netscape Communications.
[src:vitest/javascript] The differences between the two languages are more prominent than their similarities.
[src:vitest/javascript] Java has static typing, while JavaScript's typing is dynamic.
[src:vitest/javascript] Java is loaded from compiled bytecode, while JavaScript is loaded as human-readable source code.
[src:vitest/javascript] Java's objects are class-based, while JavaScript's are prototype-based.
[src:vitest/javascript] Finally, Java did not support functional programming until Java 8, while JavaScript has done so from the beginning, being influenced by Scheme.
[src:vitest/javascript] JSON is a data format derived from JavaScript; hence the name JavaScript Object Notation.
[src:vitest/javascript] It is a widely used format supported by many other programming languages.
[src:vitest/javascript] Many websites are JavaScript-heavy, so transpilers have been created to convert code written in other languages, which can aid the development process.
[src:vitest/javascript] TypeScript and CoffeeScript are two notable languages that transpile to JavaScript.
[src:vitest/javascript] WebAssembly is a newer language with a bytecode format designed to complement JavaScript, especially the performance-critical portions of web page scripts.
[src:vitest/javascript] All of the major JavaScript engines support WebAssembly, which runs in the same sandbox as regular JavaScript code.
[src:vitest/javascript] asm.js is a subset of JavaScript that served as the forerunner of WebAssembly.
[src:vitest/test-automation] Automation provides many benefits over manual testing.
[src:vitest/test-automation] For API testing, tests drive the SUT via its application programming interface (API).
[src:vitest/test-automation] Compared to manual testing, automated API testing often can execute a relatively large number of cases in a relatively short time.
[src:vitest/test-automation] For GUI testing, tests drive the SUT via its graphical user interface (GUI) by generating events such as keystrokes and mouse clicks.
[src:vitest/test-automation] Automated GUI testing can be challenging to develop, but can run much faster than a human could perform the same testing.
[src:vitest/test-automation] When automated testing is in place, regression testing can be a relatively quick and easy operation.
[src:vitest/test-automation] Instead of a significant outlay of human time and effort, a regression test run could require nothing more than a push of a button and even starting the run can be automated.
[src:vitest/test-automation] The following are notable testing techniques categorized as test automation.
[src:vitest/test-automation] Continuous testing is the process of executing automated tests as part of the software delivery pipeline to assess the business risk of releasing the SUT.
[src:vitest/test-automation] The scope of testing extends from validating bottom-up requirements or user stories to assessing the system requirements associated with overarching business goals.
[src:vitest/test-automation] For model-based testing, the SUT is modeled and test cases can be generated from it to support no code test development.
[src:vitest/test-automation] Some tools support the encoding of test cases as plain English that can be used on multiple operating systems, browsers, and smart devices.
[src:vitest/test-automation] Test-driven development (TDD) inherently includes the generation of automation test code.
[src:vitest/test-automation] Unit test code is written while the SUT code is written.
[src:vitest/test-automation] When the code is complete, the tests are complete as well.
[src:vitest/test-automation] A review of 52 practitioner and 26 academic sources found that five main factors to consider in test automation decision are: system under test (SUT), scope of testing, test toolset, human and organizational topics, cross-cutting factors.
[src:vitest/test-automation] The factors most frequently identified were: need for regression testing, economic factors, and maturity of SUT.
[src:vitest/test-automation] While the reusability of automated tests is valued by software development companies, this property can also be viewed as a disadvantage as it leads to a plateau effect, where repeatedly executing the same tests stops detecting errors.
[src:vitest/test-automation] Testing tools can help automate tasks such as product installation, test data creation, GUI interaction, problem detection (consider parsing or polling agents equipped with test oracles), defect logging, etc., without necessarily automating tests in an end-to-end fashion.
[src:vitest/test-automation] To support coded automated testing, the test engineer or software quality assurance person must have software coding ability.
[src:vitest/test-automation] Some testing techniques such as table-driven and no-code can lessen or alleviate the need for programming skill.
[src:vitest/test-automation] A test automation framework provides a programming environment that integrates test logic, test data, and other resources.
[src:vitest/test-automation] The framework provides the basis of test automation and simplifies the automation effort.
[src:vitest/test-automation] Using a framework can lower the cost of test development and maintenance.
[src:vitest/test-automation] If there is change to any test case then only the test case file needs to be updated and the driver script and startup script will remain the same.
[src:vitest/test-automation] A framework is responsible for defining the format in which to express expectations, providing a mechanism to hook into or drive the SUT, executing the tests, and reporting results.
[src:vitest/test-automation] A test automation interface is a platform that provides a workspace for incorporating multiple testing tools and frameworks for system/integration testing.
[src:vitest/test-automation] A test automation interface may simplify the process of mapping tests to business criteria without coding.
[src:vitest/test-automation] A test automation interface may improve the efficiency and flexibility of maintaining tests.
[src:vitest/test-automation] The parser is present to parse the object files coming from the object repository into the test specific scripting language.
[src:vitest/test-automation] Collection of UI/Application object data recorded by the testing tool while exploring the SUT.
[src:vitest/vite-software] Vite monitors files as they are being edited and upon file save the web browser reloads the code being edited through a process called Hot Module Replacement (HMR) which works by just reloading the specific file being changed using ES6 modules (ESM) instead of recompiling the entire application.
[src:vitest/vite-software] Vite provides built-in support for server-side rendering (SSR).
[src:vitest/vite-software] By default, it listens on TCP port 5173.
[src:vitest/vite-software] It is possible to configure Vite to serve content over HTTPS and proxy requests (including WebSocket) to a back-end web server, such as Apache HTTP Server or lighttpd.
[src:vitest/vite-software] Vite has a Hot Module Replacement (HMR) system, which reduces wait times during development.
[src:vitest/vite-software] Vite supports frameworks such as React, Vue, and Svelte, and has server-side rendering (SSR), code-splitting, and asynchronous loading.
